"A spring is not a coil of metal. A spring is a rule. The rule says:
'if I am stretched, I pull my ends toward each other with a force
proportional to how far I am from my rest length; if I am compressed,
I push them apart the same way.' The coil of metal is one way to build
a thing that obeys the rule. So is a rubber band. So is the tension in
a rope. So is the force between two atoms in a molecule. Springs are
everywhere the moment you look for them.

We are going to link two entities with `world/link!`, tune the link's
rest length and stiffness with `world/link-rest!`, and watch the two
entities behave like they're connected. Then we'll chain ten of them.
Then we'll grid 225 of them into a piece of cloth and let gravity pull
it. By chapter's end you'll have a hammock you can grab with the mouse
and pull, and the hammock will sag where you pull and spring back when
you let go.

---

## 2.1 Two bodies, one spring

```scheme
;; Two entities. One spring. Watch them oscillate.
(define (two-and-a-spring)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0)                    ;; zero gravity: pure spring behavior
  (let ((a (world/spawn 'ball  80 200))
        (b (world/spawn 'ball 240 200)))
    (entity/mass! a 1.0)
    (entity/mass! b 1.0)
    (let ((link (world/link! a b)))
      (world/link-rest!      link 160)    ;; natural length = 160
      (world/link-stiffness! link 0.05)   ;; k
      (world/link-damping!   link 0.02)   ;; c
      (entity/set-vel! a -3 0)            ;; kick a to the left
      link)))

(two-and-a-spring)
(let loop ((n 300)) (world/step) (when (> n 0) (loop (- n 1))))
```

The two balls oscillate around their center of mass. Because we set
gravity to zero, the only force is the spring. Because we damped it
(`0.02`), the oscillation slowly decays; if we set damping to zero it
would ring forever, which is the sign of an ideal spring in a
frictionless universe. Real springs always have damping.

Read `world/link-stiffness!` as 'how hard the spring pulls.' Read
`world/link-damping!` as 'how much energy the spring bleeds into the
world each cycle.' Real cloth needs both. Real rope needs both. Real
hair needs both. The tuning table is Appendix F.

## 2.2 A chain — pin the top, let it swing

```scheme
;; A chain of 10 balls. The top is pinned; the rest swing.
(define (chain n rest)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.4)
  (let loop ((i 0) (prev #f) (balls '()))
    (if (>= i n)
        (reverse balls)
        (let ((b (world/spawn 'link (+ 160 (* i 2)) (+ 40 (* i rest)))))
          (entity/mass!     b 1.0)
          (entity/drag!     b 0.01)
          (when (= i 0) (entity/pin! b))         ;; top-of-chain fixed
          (when prev
            (let ((L (world/link! prev b)))
              (world/link-rest!      L rest)
              (world/link-stiffness! L 0.30)     ;; stiffer than the free spring
              (world/link-damping!   L 0.05)))
          (loop (+ i 1) b (cons b balls))))))

(chain 10 12)
(let loop ((n 500)) (world/step) (when (> n 0) (loop (- n 1))))
```

Ten balls, nine springs, gravity pulling everything down, and the top
ball pinned. Because we spawned the chain with a slight rightward
offset per step (`(+ 160 (* i 2))`), it starts out slanted and swings
across when released. `entity/drag!` is per-entity air resistance — a
tiny amount so the swing decays without being obviously suppressed.

Notice: this is the same `world/step` loop as chapter 1. All we
changed is what's IN the world before the loop starts. The engine
doesn't know it's a chain. It only knows it has some entities with
some forces.

## 2.3 A cloth — a 15×15 grid of balls with 4-neighbor springs

```scheme
;; A cloth is a 2D grid of balls linked to their 4 neighbors.
;; Pin the top row. Gravity pulls the rest. Watch it hang.
(define (cloth cols rows spacing)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (let ((g (make-vector (* cols rows))))
    ;; spawn a ball at each grid position
    (let loop-y ((r 0))
      (when (< r rows)
        (let loop-x ((c 0))
          (when (< c cols)
            (let ((b (world/spawn 'thread
                       (+ 60 (* c spacing))
                       (+ 30 (* r spacing)))))
              (entity/mass! b 0.3)
              (entity/drag! b 0.015)
              (when (= r 0) (entity/pin! b))     ;; top row pinned
              (vector-set! g (+ (* r cols) c) b))
            (loop-x (+ c 1))))
        (loop-y (+ r 1))))
    ;; link horizontal neighbors
    (let loop-y ((r 0))
      (when (< r rows)
        (let loop-x ((c 0))
          (when (< c (- cols 1))
            (let ((L (world/link!
                       (vector-ref g (+ (* r cols) c))
                       (vector-ref g (+ (* r cols) c 1)))))
              (world/link-rest!      L spacing)
              (world/link-stiffness! L 0.60)
              (world/link-damping!   L 0.06))
            (loop-x (+ c 1))))
        (loop-y (+ r 1))))
    ;; link vertical neighbors
    (let loop-y ((r 0))
      (when (< r (- rows 1))
        (let loop-x ((c 0))
          (when (< c cols)
            (let ((L (world/link!
                       (vector-ref g (+ (* r cols) c))
                       (vector-ref g (+ (* (+ r 1) cols) c)))))
              (world/link-rest!      L spacing)
              (world/link-stiffness! L 0.60)
              (world/link-damping!   L 0.06))
            (loop-x (+ c 1))))
        (loop-y (+ r 1))))
    g))

(cloth 15 15 12)
(let loop ((n 600)) (world/step) (when (> n 0) (loop (- n 1))))
```

That is real cloth. 225 balls, roughly 420 links, all managed by the
same `world/step`. It sags in the middle, curls slightly at the free
corners, and settles into a hanging shape that a wardrobe designer
would recognize.

If you want it to LOOK like cloth, add:

```scheme
(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (world/each 'thread
      (lambda (b)
        (let ((p (entity/pos b)))
          (paint-circle (car p) (cdr p) 2 white))))))
```

Two hundred and twenty-five little white circles, hanging, swaying if
you `(world/wind! 0.5 0)` for a moment. Beautiful.

## 2.4 Grab and pull — a mouse-anchored spring

Cloth you can grab is more fun than cloth you can only look at. Here
is the trick: create one extra 'grab anchor' entity that follows the
mouse, and when the user clicks, `world/link!` it to the nearest cloth
ball. When they release, delete the link.

```scheme
;; A grab handle. Follow the mouse. On click, spring-link to nearest cloth.
(define anchor #f)
(define grab-link #f)

(define (setup-grab)
  (set! anchor (world/spawn 'anchor 0 0))
  (entity/pin!  anchor)
  (entity/mass! anchor 100))

(define (update-grab)
  (let ((m (input/mouse-pos)))
    (entity/set-pos! anchor (car m) (cdr m)))
  (cond
    ((and (input/pressed? 'mouse-left) (not grab-link))
     (let ((target (world/nearest 'thread
                     (entity/x anchor) (entity/y anchor))))
       (when target
         (let ((L (world/link! anchor target)))
           (world/link-rest!      L 0)
           (world/link-stiffness! L 0.80)
           (world/link-damping!   L 0.15)
           (set! grab-link L)))))
    ((and (input/released? 'mouse-left) grab-link)
     (world/link-remove! grab-link)
     (set! grab-link #f))))

(setup-grab)
(on-frame (lambda (t) (world/step) (update-grab)))
```

`world/nearest 'thread x y` returns the cloth ball closest to the
mouse. We spring-link the anchor to that ball with rest length zero,
so the ball is pulled straight to the mouse. When the user releases,
we delete the link.

This is a general pattern: user interaction is a springable connection
between a controlled anchor and the world.

## 2.5 A hammock

Now do this: run `cloth 20 8 14` (long and narrow), pin the FIRST
column and the LAST column instead of the top row. It hangs between
two supports. That is a hammock. Add a slightly-heavier 'occupant'
ball, spring-linked to a few center threads, and it sags realistically.

```scheme
(define (hammock cols rows spacing)
  (let ((g (cloth cols rows spacing)))
    ;; Un-pin top row, pin first and last columns.
    (world/each 'thread (lambda (b) (entity/unpin! b)))
    (let loop ((r 0))
      (when (< r rows)
        (entity/pin! (vector-ref g (* r cols)))
        (entity/pin! (vector-ref g (+ (* r cols) (- cols 1))))
        (loop (+ r 1))))
    g))
```

Same primitives. Different pinning. Different physical object.
Simulation is like this — small changes to what starts pinned change
what you're simulating.

---

## 2.6 The four routing patterns in cloth

**Composition.** The cloth is composed: a spawn-grid step, a
horizontal-link step, a vertical-link step. Add diagonal links to
resist shearing, and you have exactly one more `let loop`. Add a
tear-condition (delete link when stretched past a threshold) and
you're composing damage into the same shape.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop orchestrates: read input, update
grab, `world/step`, paint. A more elaborate hammock demo orchestrates:
title screen → sag test → grab test → wind test → save the tape.

**In-routing.** When two cloth threads collide (rare unless you allow
self-collision), the engine routes to a collision handler. When the
mouse clicks, `input/pressed?` in `update-grab` is the in-route from
raw event to logic.

**Routing.** Cloth positions route to the framebuffer as circles.
Link tensions route to a debug overlay (color the link red when
stretched past 1.5× rest). Tearing events route to Cortex if you want
to remember 'this hammock's third link tore after 400 frames of that
initial condition' — the sort of persistence the runtime would use to
answer 'has this hammock design ever failed in testing?'

---

## 2.7 Common desktop tasks

An operator asked: 'if I hang a hand-knotted rope hammock from two
hooks 96 inches apart, and it holds a 180-pound person, how much sag
should I expect at rest?' A cloth simulation with realistic
stiffness/damping predicts the answer within a fraction of an inch,
compared to a bench test. That is not a toy question — that is a
listing you can put on the shop with a real number backed by a real
sim.

## 2.8 Try this

1. Halve the stiffness of all links. What does the cloth look like?
2. Double the damping. Does it stop swaying when you grab-and-release?
3. Add diagonal links. Does the cloth resist shearing?
4. Add a tear threshold: `(when (> (world/link-stretch L) 1.8)
   (world/link-remove! L))`. Pull the cloth hard. Watch a hole open.
5. Chain the hammock's two supports to a hanging plant above. Now
   you're simulating a two-support system on flexible mounts.

## 2.9 Pitfalls

**Explosion.** Stiff springs + large timestep = numerical explosion.
The link tries to correct too much per frame and overshoots. Fixes:
softer stiffness, smaller timestep, or `world/solve!` iterations to
resolve constraints multiple times per frame.

**Everything is one link away.** If your cloth is a stack of
disconnected columns, you forgot the horizontal links. Debug by
paint-drawing every link.

**The pinned-corner grid trap.** Pinning ALL four corners of a cloth
means it can't stretch and looks unnaturally flat. Pin only the top
edge, or top+bottom edges for a hanging banner, or two opposing
corners for a diamond drape.

